    id: 192,
    title: "Question 99 • Bubble Sort",
    category: LEVEL_CATEGORIES.PYTHON_BASICS,
    tag: "Question • Algorithms",
    description: "Sort a list by repeatedly swapping adjacent items that are in the wrong order.",
    concepts: ["bubble sort", "nested loops", "swap", "sorting algorithm"],
    codeExample: `def bubble_sort(arr):
    n = len(arr)
    for i in range(n):
        for j in range(0, n - i - 1):
            if arr[j] > arr[j + 1]:
                arr[j], arr[j + 1] = arr[j + 1], arr[j]
    return arr

nums = [64, 25, 12, 22, 11]
print(bubble_sort(nums))`,
    output: "[11, 12, 22, 25, 64]",
    algorithmExplanation: "The outer loop runs n times. The inner loop compares adjacent pairs and swaps them if they are in the wrong order. After each outer pass, the largest unsorted item bubbles to its correct position.",
    returnExplanation: "bubble_sort modifies the list in place and returns it.",
    returnFlow: "After the first pass, 64 is at the end. After the second, 25 is second to last. This continues until the list is sorted.",
    steps: [
        { line: 1, text: "Python registers bubble_sort." },
        { line: 9, text: "Python creates an unsorted list." },
        { line: 10, text: "Python calls bubble_sort(nums)." },
        { line: 2, text: "n becomes 5." },
        { line: 3, text: "Outer loop starts. i = 0." },
        { line: 4, text: "Inner loop compares adjacent pairs." },
        { line: 5, text: "64 > 25: swap. 64 > 12: swap. 64 > 22: swap. 64 > 11: swap." },
        { line: 5, text: "After first pass, 64 is at the end." },
        { line: 7, text: "After all passes, the list is sorted. Returns [11, 12, 22, 25, 64]." },
        { line: 10, text: "Python prints the sorted list." }
    ],
