    description: "Sort a list by repeatedly finding the minimum and swapping it into position.",
    concepts: ["selection sort", "min index", "swap", "nested loops"],
    codeExample: `def selection_sort(arr):
    n = len(arr)
    for i in range(n):
        min_idx = i
        for j in range(i + 1, n):
            if arr[j] < arr[min_idx]:
                min_idx = j
        arr[i], arr[min_idx] = arr[min_idx], arr[i]
    return arr

nums = [29, 10, 14, 37, 13]
print(selection_sort(nums))`,
    output: "[10, 13, 14, 29, 37]",
    algorithmExplanation: "For each position i, the algorithm finds the smallest value in the rest of the list and swaps it into position i.",
    returnExplanation: "selection_sort modifies arr in place and returns it.",
    returnFlow: "Pass 1: finds 10 (smallest), swaps with 29. Pass 2: finds 13, swaps with 10's old spot. Continues until sorted.",
    steps: [
        { line: 1, text: "Python registers selection_sort." },
        { line: 11, text: "Python creates [29, 10, 14, 37, 13]." },
        { line: 12, text: "Python calls selection_sort(nums)." },
        { line: 3, text: "Outer loop: i = 0. Looking for the minimum in the whole list." },
        { line: 4, text: "min_idx = 0. arr[0] = 29 is the current candidate." },
        { line: 5, text: "Inner loop finds 10 at index 1. min_idx becomes 1." },
        { line: 8, text: "Swap arr[0] and arr[1]: 29 and 10 exchange places." },
        { line: 3, text: "i = 1. Find minimum in [29, 14, 37, 13]. 13 at index 4." },
        { line: 8, text: "Continues until the list is fully sorted." },
        { line: 12, text: "Python prints [10, 13, 14, 29, 37]." }
    ],
