    id: 320,
    title: "Question 227 • The None Comparison Trap",
    category: LEVEL_CATEGORIES.PYTHON_BASICS,
    tag: "Question • Logic Bug",
    description: "Understand why you must use 'is None' instead of '== None' to safely check for None.",
    concepts: ["None comparison", "is vs ==", "__eq__ override", "identity vs equality"],
    codeExample: `class Tricky:
    def __eq__(self, other):
        return True

t = Tricky()

print(t == None)
print(t is None)

x = None
print(x == None)
print(x is None)

def process(value=None):
    if value is None:
        return "No value provided"
    return f"Got: {value}"

print(process())
print(process(0))`,
    output: `True
False
True
True
No value provided
Got: 0`,
    algorithmExplanation: "'==' calls __eq__, which can be overridden. 'is' checks object identity — whether two names point to the exact same object. None is a singleton, so 'is None' is always correct.",
    returnExplanation: "process() uses 'is None' so it correctly distinguishes None from falsy values like 0.",
    returnFlow: "t == None calls t.__eq__(None) which returns True (by override). t is None is False — t is not the None singleton. process(0): 0 is not None, so returns 'Got: 0'.",
    steps: [
        { line: 2, text: "__eq__ is overridden to always return True." },
        { line: 6, text: "t == None calls t.__eq__(None). Returns True (overridden)." },
        { line: 7, text: "t is None checks identity. t is a Tricky object, not None. False." },
        { line: 9, text: "x = None. x is the actual None singleton." },
        { line: 10, text: "x == None: True (default __eq__ for None)." },
        { line: 11, text: "x is None: True — x IS the None singleton." },
        { line: 18, text: "process(0): 0 is not None, so it returns 'Got: 0' correctly." }
    ],
