        id: 351,
        title: "UI Level 17 • CSS Selectors",
        category: LEVEL_CATEGORIES.USER_INTERFACE,
        tag: "UI Level 17 • CSS Selectors",
        description: "Learn the three core ways to select HTML elements in CSS: element selectors, class selectors, and ID selectors — the foundation of all CSS styling.",
        concepts: ["CSS selectors", "element selector", "class selector", "ID selector", "specificity", "cascade"],
        codeExample: `<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <title>CSS Selectors</title>
  <style>

    /* Element selector — styles ALL h1 tags */
    h1 {
      color: #1e40af;
      font-size: 2rem;
      text-align: center;
      margin-bottom: 24px;
    }

    /* Element selector — styles ALL p tags */
    p {
      line-height: 1.7;
      color: #374151;
      margin-bottom: 12px;
    }

    /* Class selector — starts with a dot */
    .highlight {
      background-color: #fef3c7;
      padding: 3px 8px;
      border-radius: 4px;
      font-weight: bold;
    }

    /* Class selector — reused on multiple divs */
    .card {
      background: white;
      border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;
      border-radius: 10px;
      padding: 20px;
      margin: 16px 0;
      box-shadow: 0 1px 4px rgba(0,0,0,0.06);
    }

    /* ID selector — starts with hash, matches ONE element */
    #intro {
      font-size: 1.1rem;
      border-left: 4px solid #2563eb;
      padding-left: 16px;
      margin-bottom: 24px;
    }

  </style>
</head>
<body>

  <h1>CSS Selectors Explained</h1>

  <p id="intro">CSS selectors are patterns that match HTML elements.
  They control <span class="highlight">which elements</span> get styled.</p>

  <div class="card">
    <h2>Element Selectors</h2>
    <p>These match every element of a given type. The style above applies
    to <span class="highlight">all paragraphs</span> on the page automatically.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="card">
    <h2>Class Selectors</h2>
    <p>Classes can be reused on <span class="highlight">multiple elements</span>.
    One class name, applied wherever needed.</p>
  </div>

</body>
</html>`,
